items.synopsis: Australia takes its lead beyond 300 as England's short-pitched bowling ruffles some feathers on the fourth day of the second Test at Lord's. Follow all the action in our live blog.

title.children: Australia stutters in the pursuit of a massive lead on day four at Lord's

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australia were 3-92 in that session - the bouncers doing the business again in this Test match as Smith, Head and Khawaja all fell to some short stuff from England's bowlers. Australia will still want a lot more runs in this next session though - England successfully chased 378 last summer against India, and chased three over scores between 279 and 299 that first Bazball summer. So still plenty to do all round in this match.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Lunch: Australia 5-222, lead by 313 (Green 15, Carey 10)

children.content: Australia were 3-92 in that session - the bouncers doing the business again in this Test match as Smith, Head and Khawaja all fell to some short stuff from England's bowlers.

Australia will still want a lot more runs in this next session though - England successfully chased 378 last summer against India, and chased three over scores between 279 and 299 that first Bazball summer.
So still plenty to do all round in this match.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: One brings two! Smith goes on the hook, gets a top edge to Zak Crawley in the deep and he takes a simple catch! Smith goes for 34 off 61! That's got the crowd going a bit.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: OUT! SMITH GOES TOO!

children.content: Smith goes on the hook, gets a top edge to Zak Crawley in the deep and he takes a simple catch!
That's got the crowd going a bit.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Usman Khawaja has holed out to the sub fielder Matthew Potts in the deep! That's, dare I say it, a very English dismissal against the short ball (of which there were far more than two in that over). He goes for 77 from 187 balls.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: KHAWAJA IS OUT!

children.content: Usman Khawaja has holed out to the sub fielder Matthew Potts in the deep!
That's, dare I say it, a very English dismissal against the short ball (of which there were far more than two in that over).
